Answer: This is a common interview question, the easiest I guess is using dynamic programming: Basically you go from left to right, each item keeps track of what number should be multiplied by if it is the last, then you go from right to left, each item keeps track of what number should be multiplied by if it is the first. When you get to the first, you know only the right side is needed. For example:   
int[] result = new int[input.length];   
result[input.length - 1] = input[input.length - 1];   
for(int i = input.length - 2; i > -1; i++) {   
result[i] = result[i + 1] * input[i];   
}   
int multiplier = 1;   
for(int i = 0; i < input.length; i++) {   
result[i] = result[i] * multiplier;   
multiplier = multiplier * input[i];   
}   
return result;   
The time complexity is O(n) as you need to pass through it twice   
